eel like a consensus of some kind was reached over the issue of exposure to church being necessary for religious education, some other things weren't quite resolved, such as the whole question of whether or not UU is or ought to be a recognised, organised religion and the implications surrounding atheists who choose to be UU.  So, that said:<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>ut it seems just saying something seems incongruous here causes a weird and undue amount of defensiveness and offense taken.&quot;<br>
<br>
I think the word &quot;incongruous&quot; can be taken two ways.  If you're saying that an atheist attending a UU service is somehow inappropriate or contradictory, then that is offensive, and that is how I've been reading your responses.  Thus far, your tone has suggested that UUs are at best wishy-wishy, and at worst, completely lacking the cajones to break from traditional religious culture and adopting a pseudo-Christian lifestyle in an effort to &quot;fit in&quot;.  Either way, not too flattering and a gross misconception.<br>
Perhaps you mean to say that the UUA is incompatible with your notion of what a spiritual community ought to be, that it defies your assumptions of all organised religions, in which case we have the right to try and clarify the issue without being branded &quot;defensive&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;If UU's really don't have a set belief system or want to be known as a religion then how did they get offically recognized as such?&quot;<br>
<br>
While the UUA emerged in the 1960's, Unitarianism and Universalism go back hundreds of years, and are rooted in Christianity (albeit a very liberal interpretation of it).  The principles that govern UU today were constructed by liberal Xians, even though the church (or association, if you prefer) today is open to all for free exploration of one's individual spiritualism and humanism.<br>
And anyway, heck, if Wiccans can have their own church--and you know the saying, ask 7 pagans a question, you'll get 10 answers--why can't a mish-mash of all faiths and non-faiths get together with one!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
&quot;Better to learn from my Muslim friend and her family than someone who has since left the faith or was never in it or is a minister in another recognized faith.&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually, the UU churches in this area (my own congregation, and I read of others in the newspaper) often have speakers from various faiths come and speak, either at the service or at forums open to the public.  These are not people who have left the faith (and incidentally, one can be a UU and still not abandon their faith--that's kind of the point--and I know a few bi-religious couples who have opted to join a UU church so they may attend together while retaining their individual beliefs).  And if most of the Christians I know are any indication, it's fair to say that a person who has studied world religions and mythology at the graduate level probably is more knowledgeable than the practitioner of any given religion.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sounds a lot like my sister’s Episcopal Church which is quite liberal and sounds nice, but still church and doctrine.&quot;<br>
<br>
I know you said you don't care what UU's believe, but I am curious--what exactly do you think UU's doctrine is?<br>
<br>
-Si</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 388<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/22/03 10:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  UU was never the issue, atheist kids in church was...</span><hr size=1> Firstly, I never “made pronouncements against UU”, rather stated several times that if it fits for you, then you should do it. What seems to have set everyone off is my assertion that it is not necessary to bring children to church to educate them about religion. No one here has yet disputed that in any way. In fact, I would say we all totally agree about this, but that some of us prefer to or feel church is the best path. Indeed KMT said, “Letting kids &quot;choose&quot; a religion if they want when they become adults seems unfair to me if they haven't been given some kind of religious education” and went on to explain hers get this education in church.<br>
<br>
Here is my original response—<br>
&quot;1. There is a big difference between studying something and participating in it--especially harmful things like drugs, smoking, religion...  Do parents who use this argument apply the same logic to other life lessons? I haven't met one, but perhaps. <br>
What I suspect is really at hand is exposing kids to the social benefits of religion as perceived or missed by the parents (beanie dinners and fellowship). This is where I split with these other atheist parents, I don't see this part of going to church as a &quot;gift&quot;, rather indoctrinating kids into the &quot;fun&quot; parts of religion that will make it more difficult for them to leave it later or more likely they will fall into it as adults. For many questioning religion, it is not strict theology, but the social consequences and missing of holiday fun that holds them back from making the break.”<br>
<br>
If you aren’t an atheist parent, then it seems this last part of #1 doesn’t apply to you and if you are, it’s clear I feel you are doing something you feel is right and giving something to your children (hence the word gift) along the lines of what KMT describes as, “Because I have a son and I wanted him to be exposed to an organized religion without all of the dogma and structure the Catholic Church where I was raised&quot; and what Mony described as her &quot;fondest memories growing up are being part of our neighbourhood church--ham &amp; bean suppers, junior choir, ringing the bells after service. I want that for my children” <br>
<br>
Some of us want our children exposed to or experiencing organized religion—I don’t. some feel religion is harmless—I don’t. Some feel church is the best place to learn about religion—I don’t. As an atheist I don’t think this choice is evil, but I do think raising children with religious holidays/celebrations/rituals makes it more difficult to leave religion later. If you are UU and you want your kids UU, this hardly seems like a problem—in either case I never called out UU here or made the vicious attacks some feel went on, but if you were offended, it was not my intention. If it offends you that I think taking kids to church and participating in religous rituals/celebrations socializes children and makes it harder to break from religion, then I don't know what to say except go ahead and refute or debate it with evidence or logic...or say you don't care and you WANT this for your children as these other ladies did. <br>
<br>
”2. The argument is applied to xian or xian based churches mostly, so it also seems illogical to me as the only &quot;religion&quot; being exposed here is xian. I do know of a few atheists who attend Buddhist Temples and one who goes to Synagogue, but in both cases the children are exposed to xian celebrations and theology by other family and, sadly in public schools as well.”<br>
<br>
Here I DO call out xian churches so maybe noone took issue with this. Again, no mention of UU (which I would not have considered a religion yet, since I didn’t know they were recognized by the US gov’t as one with all the perks—and yes, tax breaks are perks no matter how you slice it. If they don’t want to be a recognized religion anymore, I am quite sure this could be changed with to complaint from Uncle Sam). If it offends you that I am shocked to find UU is a gov't recognized religion or that they get tax breaks, I can't help that. I am NOT a fan of tax breaks for churches in general, which is somwhat typical of politcally active atheists so this would not be specific to UU either.<br>
<br>
”3. If you're not looking for the tradition or routine of church, the chicken dinner/fellowship stuff, and can research, teach and discuss religion without the aid of a minister or person who attended seminary at home, then church seems to be what I think most religious folks see it as---a place of worship. Why do I need to take my child to a place of worship to understand what prayer and worship is? If I want her to learn about other religions the best place is from me, a formal education, the library or a person of that religion.”<br>
<br>
I guess I’m a little confused about why this was so offensive, when Rusty made the same point by stating, “The terms &quot;church&quot; and &quot;sermon&quot; have much more of a religious meaning, and &quot;atheism&quot; has much more of a religious-rejection conotation. One can go on and on about &quot;atheism&quot; being simply a disbelief or lack of belief in god/s, but the much more typical atheist tends to reject more religiousity and religious association than that nominal definition.<br>
<br>
Also, using terms like &quot;church&quot; and &quot;sermon&quot; is more distinguishing, if you will, than more nominally &quot;social&quot; groups.”<br>
<br>
I gave the definition of church and looked up religion too since someone here pointed out that perhaps my confusion stems from a misunderstanding of that word and spirituality--<br>
I know some here don’t recognize the dictionary as a valid source of reference, but for the record religion is defined as:<br>
Main Entry: re•li•gion <br>
Pronunciation: ri-'li-j&amp;n<br>
Function: noun<br>
Etymology: Middle English religioun, from Latin religion-, religio supernatural constraint, sanction, religious practice, perhaps from religare to restrain, tie back -- more at RELY<br>
Date: 13th century<br>
1 a : the state of a religious &lt;a nun in her 20th year of religion&gt; b (1) : the service and worship of God or the supernatural (2) : commitment or devotion to religious faith or observance<br>
2 : a personal set or institutionalized system of religious attitudes, beliefs, and practices<br>
3 archaic : scrupulous conformity : CONSCIENTIOUSNESS<br>
4 : a cause, principle, or system of beliefs held to with ardor and faith<br>
- re•li•gion•less adjective<br>
<br>
Hmmm...this just makes it more odd to me that a Humanist sort of group that is organized for social activism with no set belief system or dogma applied for the status of offically recognized religion and continues to keep it. Many are claiming I don't &quot;get it&quot;, but I don't see any arguments or evidence to straighten out the apparent contradiction in terms and status. <br>
<br>
And exactly how does this last part of my post attack UU specifically and cause so much darn defensiveness, “FOR US, taking her to church would seem to be conceding that we need this religious activity to fit in, feel good and be like others because we miss the feelings and associations of church. I don't want to do that and honestly do feel it is incongruous for atheist parents, who largely agree the motivation is based in some longing for things they got from regular xian churches. That's essentially why I disagree with the logic of the assertion quoted above both from a teaching/educational and atheist parenting perspective.”<br>
And how is it so terribly different from Rusty saying-“ Well, it seems incongruous to me, but whereas it fulfills/satisfies something in your life, the more power to ya.”<br>
<br>
It was from my friends and statements on THIS board that I got the idea the social aspects of church are what is desired outside of merely providing religious instruction--but we've covered that. Frankly, if this is what you're seeking, you should be proud of it and the fact your kids will want to go to church someday just as you are raising them (UU that is). <br>
<br>
For the record, it seems incongruous still, but as I have repeated several times, agree with Rusty’s feeling that “…if you feel it’s right for you then you should do it.” And went to the trouble to spell it out this way too, “My initial reaction to atheists in church was the same, but I say--to each his own. I totally disagree that you need to have kids experience church to understand religion … UUA seems to make many people happy, and those that still yearn for the rituals and traditions of religion without the spirituality seem to find this works very well in many places.”<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
ST <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=encyclogirl1>Encyclogirl1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/22/03 11:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Kelly explained</span><hr size=1> .....the apparent contradiction you see, quite well, and several times. You seem content with what you feel UUA is, and that's grand, but you aren't seeing what it really is, and you seem comfortable resting on it being a pseudo-religion, shadowing the tenets of a faith based organization, like a deity-lite church.<br>
<br>
Do you ever wish to be in the company of people who are similiar to you? Who share the same worldview? Or do you like to always be on your own? I, personally, like to be around people who are facing the world as I am...with an open mind and heart. I don't particularly care if they are religious or not, just that there's respect all the way around. You don't need to be UUA to do that. But for me, where I live, it's a good chance for the exposure, and for the sense of community. Just because a person is anti-religious, doesn't translate into anti-community. Or at least it shouldn't. I repsect people who want to do it all on their own, but I don't think it's a liability, contradiction, or incongruous to seek community as an atheist.<br>
<br>
Other than that, I don't know what else to tell you. UUA evolved out of a formal religion, into what it is now, which is why many congregation pay taxes. Did you just gloss over that part?<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 389<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/22/03 1:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  re: UUA</span><hr size=1> Encyclogirl— “You seem content with what you feel UUA is, and that's grand, but you aren't seeing what it really is”<br>
<br>
Yeah, I’m sure the LDS ladies and others here would say the same of how I see their religion and how I see it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I don’t know what to say to that except I can only go on what you and other UU say and what my friend who attended UU tells me outside of their literature. It is surely not one of my fascinations and I admit I don't feel compelled to join so perhaps we are at the same impasse with UU that I would come to about LDS or Baptist or Islam. You don't think I &quot;get it&quot;. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :| --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/indifferent.gif ALT=":|"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
“and you seem comfortable resting on it being a pseudo-religion, shadowing the tenets of a faith based organization, like a deity-lite church.”<br>
It is not my word to call this a religion, rather a UU person. Yes, I do see it shadow church (which qualifies as faith based) in many, many respects not the least of which are tax exemptions and language. I wouldn’t say it’s deity-lite, more like deity-mixed if the descriptions here fit and some believe and some don’t and some believe in different deities, but theology clearly enters in as the denial of the trinity is one of the tenets. This establishes a stand on a xian theological issue, but like other religions may not be held by all it’s followers. <br>
<br>
I do wonder if this perception of mine that UU is &quot;shadowing...a faith based organization&quot; is bothersome to the religious UU's. Do the xian UU's get offended that their church is called a religion or that it is seen to be structured as other churches are, or is that something that bothers the atheist/agnostic members more? My pagan friend who is very spiritual didn't seem to mind as much, which is what makes me wonder.<br>
<br>
“Do you ever wish to be in the company of people who are similiar to you? Who share the same worldview?”<br>
Yes, just like Rusty does and thousands of other atheists who don’t attend church. What does this have to do with church?<br>
<br>
“I, personally, like to be around people who are facing the world as I am...with an open mind and heart. I don't particularly care if they are religious or not, just that there's respect all the way around. You don't need to be UUA to do that.”<br>
ITA, neither do you have to attend church with your children. You choose to do so because it works for you. I find it incongruous with atheism and so do not. We just disagree, there is not one more morally superior or sinful here (at least from my perspective which doesn’t even believe in sin).<br>
<br>
“Just because a person is anti-religious, doesn't translate into anti-community. Or at least it shouldn't. I repsect people who want to do it all on their own, but I don't think it's a liability, contradiction, or incongruous to seek community as an atheist.”<br>
Again, we agree. I am very involved in my community, volunteerism, environmental/political/social orgs and friendships with like-minded and not so like-minded individuals. This is really at the heart of those Humanist and atheist orgs you mentioned.<br>
<br>
“Other than that, I don't know what else to tell you. UUA evolved out of a formal religion, into what it is now, which is why many congregation pay taxes. Did you just gloss over that part?”<br>
No-I addressed it in the very next post on that thread. Those congregations that remove themselves as formally recognized religions and pay taxes up front I would not have a problem. It doesn’t seem there’s one UU approach to the tax issue so perhaps that adds to the confusion and BTW just using this  $ for other good works makes them no different than any other church using it’s tax savings as they see fit.<br>
<br>
I don’t know what to add either, except that as long as UU continue to call themselves and be recognized as a religion with churches there will be confusion that does not exist for the thousands of other social groups that are involved in activism and provide a sense of community. I refer you again to Rusty’s words-<br>
<br>
“The terms &quot;church&quot; and &quot;sermon&quot; have much more of a religious meaning, and &quot;atheism&quot; has much more of a religious-rejection conotation. One can go on and on about &quot;atheism&quot; being simply a disbelief or lack of belief in god/s, but the much more typical atheist tends to reject more religiousity and religious association than that nominal definition.<br>
<br>
Also, using terms like &quot;church&quot; and &quot;sermon&quot; is more distinguishing, if you will, than more nominally &quot;social&quot; groups.””<br>
